    <item>
      <title>Arctic Drift</title>
      <link>https://blog.jverkamp.com/2020/04/13/arctic-drift/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 13 Apr 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://blog.jverkamp.com/2020/04/13/arctic-drift/</guid>
      <description>&lt;figure class=&#34;cover-image&#34;&gt;
                &lt;a data-goodreads-type=&#34;book&#34; data-goodreads-id=&#34;2990950&#34; href=&#34;https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2990950.arctic-drift&#34;&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://blog.jverkamp.com/embeds/books/arctic-drift.jpg&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
            &lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;“You heard what the man said,” Giordino replied. “We’re going to Anchorage. Anchorage, Alaska,” he repeated lovingly. “South of the Arctic Circle. Did ever a place sound so warm and inviting?” he asked with a contented grin.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We&amp;rsquo;ve done ice before&lt;sup class=&#34;footnote-ref&#34; id=&#34;fnref:ice&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;#fn:ice&#34;&gt;1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;). We&amp;rsquo;ve done mines before[^mine]. We&amp;rsquo;ve done oil before[^oil]. We&amp;rsquo;ve even done global warming before[^warming]. At some point, these books have really started to blend together. Almost done though, so at this point I&amp;rsquo;ll see them through.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    
